Certainly! One taxonomic group of non-human animals that possess the ability to learn and exhibit social behaviors is the family **Delphinidae**. This family includes dolphins, which are well-known for their intelligence and complex social behaviors.

Here is the information formatted using LaTeX:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{amsmath}

\begin{document}

\section*{Taxonomic Group: Family Delphinidae}

Dolphins are marine mammals known for their sophisticated cognitive abilities and social structures. Here are some key points regarding their learning and social behaviors:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Learning Abilities:} Dolphins demonstrate advanced learning capabilities, including problem-solving, understanding symbolic language, and mimicry.
    \item \textbf{Social Behaviors:} They exhibit complex social interactions, such as cooperative hunting, social play, and intricate communication systems using vocalizations and body language.
    \item \textbf{Social Structure:} Dolphins often live in groups called pods, which can vary in size and structure, and they engage in cooperative behaviors that enhance the survival of the group.
\end{itemize}

\end{document}
```

This LaTeX code provides a simple document structure to present the information about the Delphinidae family, highlighting their learning abilities and social behaviors.
